Modern food became increasingly sweet.

Older herbal traditions often moved in the opposite direction.

Across Europe, the Balkans, and parts of the Middle East, bitter herbs were once considered an ordinary part of surviving summer heat, heavy meals, alcohol, physical labor, and stagnant digestion.

Many of the plants people now call weeds or “witch herbs” were once consumed deliberately because of their bitterness.

## Why Bitter Herbs Became Summer Herbs

In traditional herbal systems, summer was often associated with:
- sluggish digestion
- spoiled food
- heat exhaustion
- heaviness
- irritability after large meals

Bitter plants were believed to:
- stimulate appetite
- encourage digestion
- reduce heaviness
- “wake up” the body during heat

People often took them before meals, in wine, or as small intensely bitter drinks.

---

## Mugwort (Artemisia vulgaris)

Mugwort carried one of the strangest reputations in European folk herbalism.

It was associated with dreams, travelers, midsummer fires, exhaustion, and protection against harmful influences. But it was also consumed in small bitter preparations for digestion.

Why people used it:
- Traditionally associated with sluggish digestion
- Used before heavy meals
- Connected with midsummer traditions
- Commonly prepared as bitter tea or wine herb

Best method:

- Use very small amounts
- Steep briefly as tea
- Traditionally consumed before meals

Mugwort is intensely bitter and was rarely used casually in large quantities.

---

## Wormwood (Artemisia absinthium)

Wormwood became famous for bitterness itself.

In old traditions, it was used in alcoholic infusions, digestive tonics, and medicinal bitters long before absinthe made it notorious.

Why people used it:
- Extremely bitter
- Traditionally associated with digestion
- Used in aperitifs and bitter wines
- Connected with endurance during heat and heavy eating

Best method:

- Tiny amounts only
- Usually blended with other herbs
- Traditionally infused into alcohol or tonic wine

Historically, wormwood was respected more than loved.

---

## Yarrow (Achillea millefolium)

Yarrow appears repeatedly in battlefield medicine, midsummer rituals, and digestive remedies.

Its bitterness is lighter than wormwood but still distinct.

Why people used it:
- Traditionally associated with circulation and digestion
- Used in bitter summer tonics
- Connected with protection and wound care
- Common in folk beer and herbal wines

Best method:

- Tea or cold infusion
- Often mixed with mint or lemon balm
- Used in moderate amounts

Some traditions believed yarrow gathered during midsummer carried special strength.

---

## Dandelion (Taraxacum officinale)

Before modern salads and coffee substitutes, dandelion was simply a common bitter spring and summer plant.

Roots, leaves, and flowers were all used.

Why people used it:
- Traditionally associated with sluggish digestion
- Used after rich meals
- Common bitter tonic herb
- Connected with seasonal cleansing traditions

Best method:

- Fresh leaves in salads
- Roasted root drink
- Decoction of dried root

Dandelion remained popular partly because it was everywhere.

---

## Chicory (Cichorium intybus)

Chicory became famous as a bitter root substitute during shortages and poverty.

But its use long predates wartime coffee replacements.

Why people used it:
- Strong bitter flavor
- Traditionally associated with digestion
- Used in drinks and tonics
- Common roadside summer plant

Best method:

- Roasted root beverage
- Bitter decoction
- Mixed with coffee or barley drinks

Wild chicory growing beside roads became a familiar sight across much of Europe.

